availability.p: This resource has been designed for free consultation in association with the Sloane Consortium of UK national institutions which hold the original manuscript catalogue documents and related collections of Sir Hans Sloane. All content is reproducible as long as the source is indicated by referencing the publication and the name of the institutional owner of the original catalogue manuscript -- in this case The Natural History Museum (London).

DOI: http://doi.org/10.16995/olh.409 The raw transcriptions from digital images of the original manuscripts were commissioned by the Enlightenment Architectures project from the AEL Data company. These transcriptions were then fully compared, checked and corrected against the original documents by the research team that is also responsible for the complete TEI markup of the transcriptions.

msIdentifier.msName: Catalogue of ‘Coralls, Sponges, and some other submarines’

msItem.colophon: ‘Fossils I’ is a bound manuscript volume containing the individual separate catalogues titled ‘Coralls’; ‘Serpents’; ‘Echini’; ‘Crustacea’; ‘Starrfishes’ and ‘Humana’. These catalogues contain numbered entries that list and describe a number of the natural history specimens and objects collected by Sir Hans Sloane (1660-1753) between the 1680s and the 1750s. In total there are 364 folios that have been bound and numbered at a later date, a number of which contain manuscript markings on their versos. The Coralls section contains 1178 numbered entries, beginning at folios 1v and 2. The Serpents section contains 454 numbered entries, from folio 109. The Echini section contains 655 numbered entries, from folio 157. The Crustacea section contains of 364 numbered entries, from folio 226. The Starrfishes section contains 174 numbered entries, from folio 265. The Humana section contains 760 numbered entries from folio 277. Each individual catalogue begins at number one. The entries for Coralls and Serpents are written on both the recto and verso sides of the folios. The entries for Echini, Crustacea, Starrfishes, and Humana appear consistently only on the recto sides of the pages with additions and notes added on numerous occasions to the preceding (and therefore facing) verso. These are usually connected to an entry by the scribe’s use of an asterisk or ‘libra ponda’ (hashtag) symbol.

Hans Sloane resided in Bloomsbury Square, London and later at Chelsea Manor House. His collecting activities spanned the early modern and Enlightenment periods and are global in scope. A physician and President of the Royal Society, he was an influential figure in the intellectual developments of his time both in England and Europe. At his death his will stipulated that his collections should be bought by the State for the purposes of creating a public Museum, thereby creating the British Museum in 1753. Since that time, Sloane's collections have been divided between the British Museum, The British Library and the Natural History Museum (London): institutions which still retain most of his collections and catalogues. The provenance of these manuscript catalogues is therefore direct and accountable.

It is estimated that Sloane made at least 50 catalogues of the various parts of his collection, including his natural history collections and library. Sloane did not publish these catalogues of his collection in his lifetime, and these digital scholarly editions created by the Enlightenment Architectures project are the first ever publications of any of these catalogues. The raw transcriptions from digital images of the original manuscripts were commissioned by the Enlightenment Architectures project from the AEL Data company. These transcriptions were then fully compared, checked and corrected against the original documents by the research team that is also responsible for the complete TEI markup of the transcriptions. An article outlining the research considerations and decision making processes guiding the marking up of the Sloane collection catalogues in the framework of the Enlightenment Architectures project can be found at Ortolja-Baird, A., Pickering, V., Nyhan, J., Sloan, K. and Fleming, M., 2019. ‘Digital Humanities in the Memory Institution: The Challenges of Encoding Sir Hans Sloane’s Early Modern Catalogues of His Collections.’ Open Library of Humanities, 5(1), p.44. DOI:

Further information and further reading about his collections and catalogues can be found on the Reconstructing Sloane website and on the websites of the institutions he founded and which have contributed to this research project: The British Museum, The British Library, The Natural History Museum (London) and those in which he was closely involved, such as The Royal Society.

p.add:
Madrepora ramosa con le stremita
terminate in piano, nel modo dell' altra
detta: si vede nelle parti de suoi
tronchi molta differenza, percioctie le
parti che sono in luoco de tronchi primi, sone
sense, e bianche in modo de Coralli, le seguenti ectre sono
quasi annue aggiunte, sono rave, e deboli edi color orcuro,
e purpureo, e contenenti alquanto di sustanza simile à
membrana, onde puote argomentarsi esiore in essa
participazion di vita sensitiva, nel modo che e selle
sole marine, e melle spongie. Imperali. Edit. Nap. 1590.
pag. 721. Vene & 1672 p. 629 Porus matronalis
ramosus, extremitatibus in planum desinantibus, digiti indicis
instar. in cujus ramorum partibus magna spectatur differentia,
illis qui primorum loco sunt trunctrum denvis existentilus.
atys. instar Corallis albicantibus, sequentibus, quæ annuæ velut
accessiones sunt, rani, ac debilibus, colore obscuro & purpureo,
nonnitil substantiæ membranaceæ continuntibus vide conjuare treat, illos
vitæ sensitivæ particepes osse, parinde ac in vela marino et spongüs. Latin. 819.

A reddish coralline matter dropt on the outside of a small cockle
& adhering to it, especially near the head & in the jointing or
commissure of the valves in the form of a thin crusty covering.
From which coralline covering proceed litle stems of the com -
=mon red corall. This I suppose, as usually other coralls was -
form'd in a hole or fissure of some submarine rock wherein the
shell was lodg'd. Had in like manner as to this shell so to bottles,
bolts & other things such upon shipwracks, corallin matter & coralls
have been found accreted. These observations serve to show that
the manner of the production or as we vulgarly say the
growth of corall is very litle different from that of the incrustata
the Stalaginitæ & stalactite in the gritts & fissures of the rocks
at land & in the Chanells of those call'd petrifying waters. Mort.

into the bladder because of these stones, but not daunted because of my cautious
procedure, I examind for the urethra into wch. I introduced the probe
Immediatly a great discharge of urine, none befores, & on examining for
felt the substance of the bladder betwixt the probe in the bladder & my
finger in the vagina, satisfied in that searching further in the vagina
felt theos uteri in my Judgmt. uneven & tattered from which a pus & during the
cure a discharge of matter, she soon recovered & had afterwards an husband,
was under my care in some years after was thought to be wt. child, but never
has been yet, altho at usuall times regular.
